    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>3</m> or <m>4</m> learners
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper (one sheet per group)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Colored pencils or markers (at least three different colors)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A ruler
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On your graph paper, draw a coordinate system with <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> axes.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using your first color, draw the line <m>x + y = 6</m> on your coordinate system.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using your second color, draw the line <m>x - y = 0</m> (i.e., <m>y = x</m>) on the same coordinate system.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Now you have two lines that intersect. Where do they intersect? Find the intersection point by solving the system of equations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Shade the region that satisfies both <m>x + y \le 6</m> AND <m>x \ge y</m> using your third color.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Identify the vertices (corner points) of the shaded region.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss with your group: What does the shaded region represent? Why are the corner points important?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Share your observations with the class.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                To find the intersection of two lines, solve the system of equations simultaneously. For example, if you have <m>x + y = 6</m> and <m>y = x</m>, substitute the second equation into the first: <m>x + x = 6</m>, so <m>x = 3</m> and <m>y = 3</m>. The intersection is at <m>(3, 3)</m>.
            </p>
        </hint>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Solving a system of linear inequalities in two unknowns means finding all points <m>(x, y)</m> that satisfy <term>all</term> of the inequalities simultaneously. The solution is represented as a shaded region (called the <term>feasible region</term>) on a coordinate plane.
        </p>
        <p>
            The process for solving a system of linear inequalities graphically:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Graph each inequality separately on the same coordinate plane, using the five-step method from the previous section (draw boundary line, use dashed/solid line, test a point, determine which side, shade the region).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The solution to the system is the region where all the shaded regions <term>overlap</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The vertices (corner points) of the feasible region are particularly important. They occur where boundary lines intersect and can often be found by solving pairs of boundary line equations simultaneously.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For optimization problems, test the vertices to find maximum or minimum values of a given expression.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            Systems of linear inequalities are used extensively in real-world applications, especially in business and agriculture, where resources are limited and we need to find the best possible solution within those constraints.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following inequalities graphically:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x + y &amp; \le 5</mrow>
                    <mrow>x &amp; \ge 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y &amp; \ge 0</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We need to graph all three inequalities on the same coordinate plane and find where they all overlap.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The first inequality <m>x + y \le 5</m> has boundary line <m>x + y = 5</m>, passing through <m>(0, 5)</m> and <m>(5, 0)</m>. Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: <m>0 + 0 \le 5</m> is true, so we shade the region containing the origin (below and to the left of the line).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The inequality <m>x \ge 0</m> represents the region to the right of and on the <m>y</m>-axis.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The inequality <m>y \ge 0</m> represents the region above and on the <m>x</m>-axis.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The feasible region is the area where all three conditions are satisfied simultaneously. This forms a triangle with vertices at <m>(0, 0)</m>, <m>(5, 0)</m>, and <m>(0, 5)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % 1. Draw a clean, light grid
                            \draw[gray!20, thin] (-1,-1) grid (6,6);
                            
                            % 2. Shade the feasible region first (Layering practice: shade beneath lines)
                            \fill[fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (0,5) -- cycle;
                            
                            % 3. Draw axes with clean, extended arrows to prevent nodes hanging outside the area
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (7,0) node[right=2pt] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,7) node[above=2pt] {$y$};
                            
                            % 4. Draw the boundary constraint line (x + y = 5) extended beautifully
                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5, 5.5) -- (5.5, -0.5); 
                            
                            % 5. Draw tick marks and numerical labels cleanly
                            \foreach \x in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                            }
                            
                            % IMPROVEMENT: Moved 0 down and left so it doesn't overcover the (0,0) point
                            \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                            
                            % 6. Mark the vertices safely
                            \fill[black] (0,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \fill[black] (5,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \fill[black] (0,5) circle (2.5pt);
                            
                            % IMPROVEMENT: Vertex labels positioned neatly without overlapping the line tags
                            \node at (0,0) [above left=2pt] {$(0,0)$};
                            \node at (5,0) [above right=1pt] {$(5,0)$};
                            \node at (0,5) [above right=2pt] {$(0,5)$};
                            
                            % IMPROVEMENT: Line equations centered and aligned directly along the paths
                            \node at (2.5, 2.5) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-45, yshift=-1pt] {$x + y = 5$};
                            \node at (2.5, 0) [below=12pt, font=\small] {$y = 0$};
                            \node at (0, 2.5) [left=12pt, font=\small] {$x = 0$};
                            
                            % 8. Label the inside shaded region clearly as the solution region
                            \node at (1.2, 1.2) [font=\small, color=blue!80!black] {Feasible Region};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve this linear inequalities graphically:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x + y &amp; \gt 2</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x - y &amp; \le 4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then find the intersection point of the boundary lines.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>x + y \gt 2</m>: The boundary line is <m>x + y = 2</m>, which passes through <m>(0, 2)</m> and <m>(2, 0)</m>. Since this is a strict inequality, we use a dashed line. Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: <m>0 + 0 \gt 2</m> is false, so we shade the region that does NOT contain the origin (above the line).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>2x - y \le 4</m>: We rewrite as <m>y \ge 2x - 4</m>. The boundary line is <m>y = 2x - 4</m>, with <m>y</m>-intercept <m>-4</m> and slope <m>2</m>. Since this is an inclusive inequality, we use a solid line. Testing <m>(0, 0)</m>: <m>2(0) - 0 \le 4</m> is true, so we shade the region containing the origin (below the line).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The feasible region is where both shaded regions overlap.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To find the intersection point of the boundary lines, we solve:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>x + y &amp; = 2</mrow>
                                <mrow>2x - y &amp; = 4</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Adding these equations: <m>3x = 6</m>, so <m>x = 2</m>. Substituting: <m>2 + y = 2</m>, so <m>y = 0</m>. The intersection point is <m>(2, 0)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % 1. Clean background grid matching the coordinate bounds
                            \draw[gray!15, thin] (-3,-5) grid (6,6);
                            
                            % 2. FIXED SHADING: Explicitly bounded to stay strictly left/above the line 2x - y = 4 
                            % Coordinates follow the boundary intersection logic precisely
                            \fill[fill=purple!15, opacity=0.6] (2,0) -- (5,6) -- (-3,6) -- (-3,5) -- cycle;
                            
                            % 3. Axis arrows with room for labels
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (6,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,6) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                            
                            % 4. Draw boundary lines extended fully across the grid
                            \draw[dashed, thick, black] (-3,5) -- (6,-4); % x + y = 2
                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5,-5) -- (5,6); % 2x - y = 4
                            
                            % 5. Standard clean tick labeling
                            \foreach \x in {-2, -1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {-4, -3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                            }
                            \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                            
                            % 6. Intersection Dot
                            \fill[black] (2,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            
                            % FIXED INTERSECTION LABEL: Shifted upward-right with a clear background 
                            % to erase any overlapping grid lines or axis lines automatically.
                            \node at (2.2, 0.5) [right, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1.5pt, rounded corners=1pt] {$(2, 0)$};
                            
                            % FIXED LINE LABELS: Shifted slightly off the lines (using sloped offsets) 
                            % so they sit adjacent to the paths instead of directly on top of them.
                            \node at (0, 2) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-45, yshift=2pt, fill=white, inner sep=1.5pt] {$x + y = 2$};
                            \node at (3.5, 3) [above left, font=\small, rotate=63.4, xshift=-2pt, fill=white, inner sep=1.5pt] {$2x - y = 4$};
                            
                            % 8. Feasible Region Identification Text
                            \node at (1.2, 4.5) [font=\small, color=purple!80!black, font=\bfseries] {Feasible Region};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Shimala</em> bakery produces two types of snacks: <term>chapati</term> and <term>mandazi</term>. Each batch of chapati requires <m>2</m> kg of flour and <m>1</m> hour of labor. Each batch of mandazi requires <m>1</m> kg of flour and <m>2</m> hours of labor. The bakery has a maximum of <m>12</m> kg of flour and <m>9</m> hours of labor available per day.
            </p>
            <p>
                Let <m>p</m> represent the number of batches of chapati and <m>m</m> represent the number of batches of mandazi.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Write the constraints as inequalities.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph the feasible region.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the vertices of the feasible region.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If the bakery makes a profit of KSh <m>500</m> per batch of chapati and KSh <m>400</m> per batch of mandazi, what production combination maximizes profit?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The constraints are:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Flour constraint: <m>2p + m \le 12</m></li>
                                <li>Labor constraint: <m>p + 2m \le 9</m></li>
                                <li>Non-negativity: <m>p \ge 0</m> and <m>m \ge 0</m></li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph showing the feasible region bounded by these constraints:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <image>
                                <latex-image>
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                        % 1. Light background grid
                                        \draw[gray!20, thin] (-1,-1) grid (8,8);
                                        
                                        % 2. Shade feasible region safely beneath boundary lines
                                        \fill[fill=green!20, opacity=0.6] (0,0) -- (6,0) -- (5,2) -- (0,4.5) -- cycle;
                                        
                                        % 3. FIXED AXES: Changed vertical axis from (0,0) to (0,8) so it doesn't hang into negative space,
                                        % and extended the positive limits to clear the grid border cleanly.
                                        \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (-1,0) -- (8,0) node[right=4pt] {$p$ (chapati batches)};
                                        \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,8) node[above=4pt] {$m$ (mandazi batches)};
                                        
                                        % 4. Draw constraint lines kept perfectly within grid limits
                                        \draw[solid, thick, black] (2,8) -- (6.5,-1);  % 2p + m = 12
                                        \draw[solid, thick, black] (-1,5) -- (8,0.5);   % p + 2m = 9
                                        
                                        % 5. Mark vertices
                                        \fill[black] (0,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                        \fill[black] (6,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                        \fill[black] (5,2) circle (2.5pt);
                                        \fill[black] (0,4.5) circle (2.5pt);
                                        
                                        % 6. FIXED REPOSITIONED LABELS: Shifted origin elements to clear all text overlap
                                        \node at (-0.3,-0.3) [font=\small] {0};
                                        \node at (0,0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,0)$};
                                        \node at (6,0) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(6,0)$};
                                        \node at (5,2) [above right=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(5,2)$};
                                        \node at (0,4.5) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,4.5)$};
                                        
                                        % 7. Tick marks and numbering (Starting from 1 to keep origin clear)
                                        \foreach \x in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7} {
                                            \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                                        }
                                        \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7} {
                                            \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                                        }
                                        
                                        % 8. White-backed equation path labels
                                        \node at (3.2, 5.6) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-63.4, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$2p + m = 12$};
                                        \node at (2.5, 3.25) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-26.5, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$p + 2m = 9$};
                                        
                                        % NEW: Non-negativity boundary labels placed mid-span alongside the axes
                                        \node at (3, 0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$m = 0$};
                                        \node at (0, 3) [below=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$p = 0$};

                                        \node at (1.8, 1.8) [font=\small, color=green!60!black, font=\bfseries] {Feasible Region};
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The vertices of the feasible region are:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><m>(0, 0)</m> - Production baseline (zero profit).</li>
                                <li><m>(6, 0)</m> - Flour boundary limit intercept when <m>m = 0</m>.</li>
                                <li><m>(0, 4.5)</m> - Labor boundary limit intercept when <m>p = 0</m>.</li>
                                <li><m>(5, 2)</m> - Optimal intersection point found by solving the constraint equations simultaneously.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The objective function representing daily profit is <m>P = 500p + 400m</m>. Evaluating this function at each vertex:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>At <m>(0, 0)</m>: <m>P = 500(0) + 400(0) = \text{KSh } 0</m></li>
                                <li>At <m>(6, 0)</m>: <m>P = 500(6) + 400(0) = \text{KSh } 3,000</m></li>
                                <li>At <m>(0, 4.5)</m>: <m>P = 500(0) + 400(4.5) = \text{KSh } 1,800</m></li>
                                <li>At <m>(5, 2)</m>: <m>P = 500(5) + 400(2) = 2500 + 800 = \text{KSh } 3,300</m></li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The maximum profit occurs at the vertex <m>(5, 2)</m>. Therefore, Shimala bakery maximizes its daily income by producing <term>5 batches of chapati</term> and <term>2 batches of mandazi</term>, yielding a total profit of <term>KSh 3,300</term>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the following system of linear inequalities graphically on a coordinate plane:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x + y &amp; \le 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>x &amp; \ge 0</mrow>
                        <mrow>y &amp; \ge 0</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Identify the vertices of the resulting feasible region and label the boundary lines.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The feasible region is a closed triangular region in the first quadrant bounded by three constraint lines. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % 1. Light background grid
                                \draw[gray!20, thin] (-1,-1) grid (6,6);
                                
                                % 2. Shade feasible region safely beneath boundary lines
                                \fill[fill=blue!20, opacity=0.6] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,4) -- cycle;
                                
                                % 3. MATCHED AXES: Starts at -1 with single-direction arrowheads to create the exact same overhang
                                \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (-1,0) -- (5.5,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                                \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,5.5) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                                
                                % 4. Draw constraint line extended past intercepts cleanly
                                \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5,4.5) -- (4.5,-0.5);
                                
                                % 5. Mark vertices with crisp dots
                                \fill[black] (0,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                \fill[black] (4,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                \fill[black] (0,4) circle (2.5pt);
                                
                                % 6. MATCHED LABELS: Implemented your white-backed origin and vertex placement style
                                \node at (-0.3,-0.3) [font=\small] {0};
                                \node at (0,0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,0)$};
                                \node at (4,0) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(4,0)$};
                                \node at (0,4) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,4)$};
                                
                                % 7. Tick marks and numbering starting from 1 to keep origin clear
                                \foreach \x in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                    \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                                }
                                \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                    \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                                }
                                
                                % 8. White-backed equation path labels running parallel
                                \node at (2, 2) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-45, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$x + y = 4$};
                                
                                % MATCHED NON-NEGATIVITY: Placed mid-span along axes with white boxes over the grid lines
                                \node at (2, 0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$y = 0$};
                                \node at (0, 2) [below=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$x = 0$};
                                
                                \node at (1.2, 1.1) [font=\footnotesize, color=blue!85!black, font=\bfseries, align=center] {Feasible\\Region};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The vertices of the feasible region are visually identified at the boundary intersections: <m>(0, 0)</m>, <m>(4, 0)</m>, and <m>(0, 4)</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the following linear inequalities graphically:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x + y &amp; \gt 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x - y &amp; \le 4</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Find the exact intersection point of the two boundary lines algebraically and mark its position on your graph.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To find the exact vertex where the boundary lines meet, we solve the equations simultaneously:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x + 2y &amp; = 4 \quad \text{--- (Equation 1)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x - y &amp; = 4 \quad \text{--- (Equation 2)}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    From Equation 2, we isolate <m>y</m>: <m>y = 2x - 4</m>. Substituting this into Equation 1 gives:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x + 2(2x - 4) &amp; = 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>x + 4x - 8 &amp; = 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>5x &amp; = 12 \implies x = 2.4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Substituting <m>x = 2.4</m> back gives <m>y = 2(2.4) - 4 = 0.8</m>. The intersection point is <m>(2.4, 0.8)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The boundary line <m>x + 2y = 4</m> is drawn as a <em>dashed line</em> because it is a strict inequality (<m>\gt</m>), while <m>2x - y = 4</m> is drawn as a <em>solid line</em> (<m>\le</m>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    <image>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % 1. Balanced background grid
                                \draw[gray!20, thin] (-3,-5) grid (6,6);
                                
                                % 2. FIXED SHADING: Smoothly follows the boundary wall straight up to the grid ceiling (y=6)
                                \fill[fill=purple!15, opacity=0.6] (2.4,0.8) -- (5,6) -- (-3,6) -- (-3,3.5) -- cycle;
                                
                                % 3. CLEAN AXES: Unified lengths going from -3 to 6 to frame the grid completely
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-3,0) -- (6,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                                \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,6) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                                
                                % 4. FIXED BOUNDARY LINES: Truncated to stop exactly at the grid margins
                                \draw[dashed, thick, black] (-3,3.5) -- (6,-1);   % x + 2y = 4
                                \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5,-5) -- (5,6);    % 2x - y = 4
                                
                                % 5. Intersection vertex point marker
                                \fill[black] (2.4,0.8) circle (2.5pt);
                                \node at (2.4,0.8) [above right=6pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$(2.4, 0.8)$};
                                
                                % 6. Clean tick loops spanning the full grid area
                                \foreach \x in {-2, -1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                    \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                                }
                                \foreach \y in {-4, -3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                    \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                                }
                                \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                                
                                % 7. REPOSITIONED LINE LABELS: Shifted upwards along the paths to prevent clashing with the x-axis
                                \node at (-1.5, 2.75) [above left, font=\small, rotate=-26.5, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$x + 2y = 4$};
                                \node at (4.2, 4.4) [above left, font=\small, rotate=63.4, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$2x - y = 4$};
                                
                                % 8. Feasible Region Title Tag
                                \node at (0.2, 4.2) [font=\small, color=purple!80!black, font=\bfseries] {Feasible Region};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A local textile workshop in <em>Ekitale</em> produces two types of high-quality fabric garments: <term>kitenge</term> (traditional patterned wear) and <term>kikoi</term> (casual woven wrap cloth). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Each bolt of kitenge requires <m>3</m> meters of raw material and <m>2</m> hours of labor. Each bolt of kikoi requires <m>2</m> meters of raw material and <m>4</m> hours of labor. The workshop manager has a maximum of <m>24</m> meters of raw material fabric and <m>32</m> hours of labor available per week.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Let <m>x</m> represent the number of bolts of kitenge and <m>y</m> represent the number of bolts of kikoi produced per week.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write down the linear inequalities that represent this situation.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Graph the constraints on a grid system and shade the common feasible region.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find all the vertices (corner points) of your shaded region.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the workshop secures a clear profit of KSh <m>1,200</m> per bolt of kitenge and KSh <m>1,500</m> per bolt of kikoi, determine the optimal production combination to maximize weekly profit.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The linear inequalities representing the situation are:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Raw material fabric limit: <m>3x + 2y \le 24</m></li>
                                    <li>Labor time limit: <m>2x + 4y \le 32</m> (or simplified as <m>x + 2y \le 16</m>)</li>
                                    <li>Non-negativity boundaries: <m>x \ge 0</m> and <m>y \ge 0</m></li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The boundary graph of the feasible production zone is drawn below:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <image>
                                    <latex-image>
                                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                            % 1. Balanced background grid
                                            \draw[gray!20, thin] (-1,-1) grid (10,10);
                                            
                                            % 2. Safe green feasible production zone shading
                                            \fill[fill=green!20, opacity=0.6] (0,0) -- (8,0) -- (4,6) -- (0,8) -- cycle;
                                            
                                            % 3. FIXED AXES: Starts at -1 with single arrows for a perfect crosshair overhang
                                            \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (-1,0) -- (10,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$ (kitenge bolts)};
                                            \draw[black, thick, -&gt;] (0,-1) -- (0,10) node[above=4pt] {$y$ (kikoi bolts)};
                                            
                                            % 4. Constraint lines extended across the grid
                                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (1.33,10) -- (8.67,-1); % 3x + 2y = 24
                                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-1,8.5) -- (10,3);     % x + 2y = 16
                                            
                                            % 5. Clear Vertex point markers
                                            \fill[black] (0,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                            \fill[black] (8,0) circle (2.5pt);
                                            \fill[black] (4,6) circle (2.5pt);
                                            \fill[black] (0,8) circle (2.5pt);
                                            
                                            % 6. FIXED LABELS: Shifted labels to clear origin clutter
                                            \node at (-0.3,-0.3) [font=\small] {0};
                                            \node at (0,0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,0)$};
                                            \node at (8,0) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(8,0)$};
                                            \node at (4,6) [above right=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(4,6)$};
                                            \node at (0,8) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,8)$};
                                            
                                            % 7. Grid Ticks
                                            \foreach \x in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9} {
                                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                                            }
                                            \foreach \y in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9} {
                                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                                            }
                                            
                                            % 8. Parallel equation paths with clean white backgrounds
                                            \node at (6.2, 2.7) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-56.3, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$3x + 2y = 24$};
                                            \node at (7, 4.5) [above right, font=\small, rotate=-26.5, fill=white, inner sep=1.2pt] {$x + 2y = 16$};
                                            
                                            % Axis constraints over lines
                                            \node at (5, 0) [left=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$y = 0$};
                                            \node at (0, 4.5) [below=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$x = 0$};
                                            
                                            % FIXED: Folded label text onto two centered rows
                                            \node at (2.2, 2.2) [font=\footnotesize, color=green!60!black, font=\bfseries, align=center] {Feasible\\Region};
                                        \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Evaluating boundary intercept equations simultaneously gives four clean corner vertices:
                                <ul>
                                    <li><m>(0, 0)</m> - Base origin.</li>
                                    <li><m>(8, 0)</m> - Fabric limit <m>x</m>-intercept when <m>y = 0</m>.</li>
                                    <li><m>(0, 8)</m> - Labor limit <m>y</m>-intercept when <m>x = 0</m>.</li>
                                    <li><m>(4, 6)</m> - Intersection point of the two constraint paths.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The objective function representing net profit is <m>P = 1200x + 1500y</m>. Testing the four corner vertices:
                                <ul>
                                    <li>At <m>(0, 0)</m>: <m>P = 1200(0) + 1500(0) = \text{KSh } 0</m></li>
                                    <li>At <m>(8, 0)</m>: <m>P = 1200(8) + 1500(0) = \text{KSh } 9,600</m></li>
                                    <li>At <m>(0, 8)</m>: <m>P = 1200(0) + 1500(8) = \text{KSh } 12,000</m></li>
                                    <li>At <m>(4, 6)</m>: <m>P = 1200(4) + 1500(6) = 4800 + 9000 = \text{KSh } 13,800</m></li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Comparing the values shows that the highest yield occurs at vertex <m>(4,6)</m>. Therefore, to maximize profit, the workshop should produce <em>4 bolts of kitenge</em> and <em>6 bolts of kikoi</em> weekly, resulting in a maximum profit of <strong>KSh 13,800</strong>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

